data.title: Project based custom editors
data.body:
This PR opens up the ability to create custom editors inside the projects, opening up the door to creating web based code generators (ie, create a visual editor for conversation trees that saves out as javascript).  Some fixes are also included in this
- fixes an issue where if you close a project, the editors weren't closing so if you opened another project the editors would show up
- fixes an issue where the web view was not able to successfully send up a block of code and a filename to save it as (this will be critical to the TypeScript compilation ability)

data.body: Fixes #792

data.title: Project techniques and shaders
data.body:
Added ability to reference custom shaders and techniques from inside atomic projects.
- Requires a root 'Techniques' folder within the Resource folder of a project. 
- Shaders must be kept inside a 'Shaders/HLSL' or 'Shaders/GLSL' folder within the project. 
- Project specific techniques will appear in the techniques select list of the Material Inspector under a drop down called 'Project' if they exist.

data.title: Renaming assets in project rename all active scenes in Editor
data.body: If you rename an asset in the project frame, it will rename all scenes open in the editor view with that name and extension type, and use the renamed assets saving location. Seems to only be doing it for scenes in the editor, and not .js files or other supported editing formats.

data.title: Populate Material parameters with assigned shader variables
data.body: When assigning a technique to a material, we need to add any global variables from the shader in use as material parameters. For example: If assigning the water shader to a new material, the scroll speed and noise strength variables don't get added to the material parameters to be edited in the inspector.
